{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 {\f1 Backup} \u8212- Save all VM classes from vCenter to a JSON file\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This operation queries every VM class currently defined on vCenter and writes them to a JSON file in the same format as {\f1 vmClasses.json}. The backup file can be used directly with {\f1 -Action Update} to restore or re-apply classes to any vCenter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default output filename embeds the vCenter name so that backups from multiple environments are easy to distinguish at a glance:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 vmClasses-backup-vcenter.example.com.json\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pass {\f1 -JsonPath} to override the output path. Pass {\f1 -Force} to overwrite an existing file without prompting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 # Backup to the default file\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Backup -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser administrator@vsphere.local\line
\line
# Backup to a dated file and overwrite without prompting\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Backup -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser administrator@vsphere.local `\line
    -JsonPath .\\backup-$(Get-Date -Format yyyyMMdd).json -Force\line
\line
# Example\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Backup -VcenterServer source-vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser administrator@vsphere.local\line
\line
[ADVISORY] Using vCenter password from $env:VCENTER_PASSWORD. Unset the variable to be prompted interactively.\line
