{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 {\f1 Update} \u8212- Apply VM class definitions to vCenter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reads the JSON file and applies each entry to vCenter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Applies the following operations as needed:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Create} \u8212- class does not yet exist on vCenter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Patch} \u8212- class exists but differs from the file\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skip} \u8212- class already matches the file\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a class name matches one of the 16 built-in default names, the script logs a {\f1 [WARNING]} and \u8212- in interactive sessions \u8212- asks for confirmation before proceeding.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use {\f1 -VmClassName all} to process every entry, or pass a specific class name to target one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 # Apply all classes from vmClasses.json\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Update -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local -VmClassName all\line
\line
# Apply or update a single named class\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Update -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local `\line
    -VmClassName my-gpu-class\line
\line
# Dry-run (no changes are made)\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Update -WhatIf -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local -VmClassName all\line
\line
\line
# Example\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Update -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser administrator@vsphere.local -VmClassName all\line
\line
[ADVISORY] Using vCenter password from $env:VCENTER_PASSWORD. Unset the variable to be prompted interactively.\line
[INFO] Connecting to vCenter "vcenter.example.com"...\line
[INFO] Creating VM class "32cpu-besteffort-262144mb-besteffort"... Succeeded\line
[INFO] Creating VM class "2cpu-besteffort-8192mb-besteffort"... Succeeded\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 {\f1 Delete} \u8212- Remove a VM class from vCenter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Delete no longer reads from the JSON file. Instead it queries vCenter directly and operates only on {\b custom} classes (the 16 built-in defaults are always excluded and not shown).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b {\f1 -VmClassName all}} \u8212- deletes every custom class found on vCenter, logging how many built-in defaults were skipped.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b {\f1 -VmClassName <name>}} \u8212- deletes the named class directly (no JSON lookup).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 # Interactive: choose from custom classes on vCenter\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Delete -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local\line
\line
# Delete all custom classes (built-in defaults are preserved)\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Delete -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local `\line
    -VmClassName all\line
\line
# Delete one specific class by name\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Delete -VcenterServer vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser admininstrator@vsphere.local `\line
    -VmClassName my-gpu-class\line
\line
# Example\line
.\\Manage-VMClasses.ps1 -Action Delete -VcenterServer vdest-vcenter.example.com -VcenterUser administrator@vsphere.local -VmClassName 32cpu-besteffort-262144mb-besteffort\line
\line
[ADVISORY] Using vCenter password from $env:VCENTER_PASSWORD. Unset the variable to be prompted interactively.\line
[INFO] Connecting to vCenter "dest-vcenter.example.com"...\line
[INFO] Deleting VM class "32cpu-besteffort-262144mb-besteffort"... Succeeded\par}
